[h1]City Remake[/h1]

[b]Overview[/b]
City Remake is a systemic overhaul of EU5's urbanization model. Its goal is not to let locations level up automatically just by meeting a few abstract numbers, but to make the growth of villages, towns, and cities depend far more on infrastructure, estate investment, and long-term development.

[b]Main Features[/b]
[list]
[*]Reworks the growth path from rural settlement to town, and from town to city.
[*]Moves part of the vanilla town and city benefits into buildable infrastructure.
[*]Adds a full set of prerequisite rural infrastructure so the countryside can also accumulate prosperity and gradually qualify for urbanization.
[*]Creates an upgrade chain between rural infrastructure and town/city infrastructure instead of simply deleting the old layer and replacing it.
[*]Adds distinct urbanization paths and signature buildings for the Nobility, Clergy, and Burghers.
[*]Makes prosperity, control, market access, religion, and estate finances far more important to urban growth.
[/list]

[b]Design Direction[/b]
[list]
[*]Rural settlements are no longer just a blank stage before urbanization. They must first assemble the most basic market, administrative, religious, craft, storage, and sanitation infrastructure.
[*]Towns and cities are no longer just rank labels. Their functions must be realized through sustained infrastructure investment.
[*]Urban centers driven by different estates develop different tendencies: nobles focus on governance and frontiers, clergy on religion and learning, and burghers on markets and trade.
[*]Urbanization is no longer a question of "Can you click the upgrade button?", but of "Has this location truly completed the structural transformation from countryside to city?"
[/list]

[b]Recommended For[/b]
[list]
[*]Players who enjoy slower internal development and long-term construction planning.
[*]Players who want city growth to feel more staged, more expensive, and more deliberate.
[*]Players who enjoy shaping different urban paths through estates, buildings, and local conditions.
[/list]

[b]Notes[/b]
This mod is still being tuned. Many values, upkeep demands, and AI priorities will continue to be adjusted based on actual play experience. The overall direction will remain the same: to make the urban system more layered, more meaningful, and more worth investing in.

Feedback is welcome if you encounter bugs or balance issues.
